  "notes": "Interslavic (medžuslovjansky) — a zonal constructed language based on the common features of the Slavic languages. Its Latin orthography is deliberately regular: each letter has a fixed value, with a range of accepted regional realisations (č/š/ž may be alveolo-palatal or retroflex; ⟨g⟩ may be [ɦ]). ⟨ě⟩ is the yat letter, most commonly [jɛ]. Optional etymological letters (å, ę, ų, ė, ȯ, ć, đ, ĺ, ń, ŕ, ś, ź) carry Proto-Slavic information and are not part of the base flavorisation; they are omitted here. A Cyrillic orthography exists in parallel.",
